Step 4A - Do charges of people who smoke differ significantly from the people who don't?¶

Step 1: State the null and alternative hypothesis:¶

  • Null hypothesis: $H_0:$ Charges of people who smoke and do not smoke are same, $\mu_{Smokers} = \mu_{Non-Smokers}$
  • Alternative hypothesis: $H_A:$ Charges of people who smoke and do not smoke are not same, $\mu_{Smokers} \neq \mu_{Non-Smokers}$
  • Here $\mu$ is the mean insurance charges paid by smokers or non-smokers.

Step 2: Decide the significance level¶

  • Selecting α = 0.05

Step 3: Identify the test statistic¶

  • Since we have to check if the mean of two samples for charges $\overline {x}_{Smokers}$ and $\overline {x}_{Non-Smokers}$ are significantly different, selecting two sample t-test for mean.
$$t = {\dfrac {\overline {x}_1-\overline {x}_2}{\sqrt{{\dfrac {s^2_1}{n_1}}+{\dfrac {s^2_2}{n_2}}}}}$$

Step 4: Calculate p value¶

In [27]:
group1 = df[df['Smoker'] == 'yes']['Charges']
group2 = df[df['Smoker'] == 'no']['Charges']
print(' x̄ 𝑆𝑚𝑜𝑘𝑒𝑟𝑠:', round(group1.mean(),4),"\n",'x̄ 𝑁𝑜𝑛−𝑆𝑚𝑜𝑘𝑒𝑟𝑠:', round(group2.mean(),4))

t_statistic, p_value = ttest_ind(group1, group2)
print('t-statistic is %1.6f' %(t_statistic), '| p-value is %1.6f' %(p_value))

 x̄ 𝑆𝑚𝑜𝑘𝑒𝑟𝑠: 32050.2318 
 x̄ 𝑁𝑜𝑛−𝑆𝑚𝑜𝑘𝑒𝑟𝑠: 8440.6603
t-statistic is 46.644795 | p-value is 0.000000

Step 5: Decide to 'Reject' or 'Fail to reject' the null hypothesis¶

  • Statistical evidence, p-value is 0.000000 and < 0.05 α so we 'Reject the null hypothesis'.
  • Supporting $H_A:$ Charges of people who smoke and do not smoke are significantly different, $\overline {x}_{Smokers} \neq \overline {x}_{Non-Smokers}$

Step 4B - Does bmi of males differ significantly from that of females?¶

Step 1: State the null and alternative hypothesis:¶

  • Null hypothesis: $H_0:$ BMI of males and females are same, $\mu_{Males} = \mu_{Females}$
  • Alternative hypothesis: $H_A:$ BMI of males and females are not same, $ \mu_{Males} \neq \mu_{Females}$
  • Here $\mu$ is the mean of bmi grouped by gender.

Step 2: Decide the significance level¶

  • Selecting α = 0.05

Step 3: Identify the test statistic¶

  • Since we have to check if the mean for two samples of BMI $\overline {x}_{Males}$ and $\overline {x}_{Females}$ are significantly different, selecting two sample t-test for mean.
$$t = {\dfrac {\overline {x}_1-\overline {x}_2}{\sqrt{{\dfrac {s^2_1}{n_1}}+{\dfrac {s^2_2}{n_2}}}}}$$

Step 4: Calculate p value¶

In [28]:
group1 = df[df['Gender'] == 'male']['BMI']
group2 = df[df['Gender'] == 'female']['BMI']
print(' x̄ 𝑀𝑎𝑙𝑒𝑠:', round(group1.mean(),4),"\n",'x̄ 𝐹𝑒𝑚𝑎𝑙𝑒𝑠:', round(group2.mean(),4))

t_statistic, p_value = ttest_ind(group1, group2)

Step 5: Decide to 'Reject' or 'Fail to reject' the null hypothesis¶

  • Statistical evidence, p-value is 0.089976 and > 0.05 α so we 'Fail to reject the null hypothesis'.
  • Supporting $H_0:$ BMI of males and females are same, $\overline {x}_{Males} = \overline {x}_{Females}$

Step 4C - Is the proportion of smokers significantly different in different genders?¶

Step 1: State the null and alternative hypothesis:¶

  • Null hypothesis: $H_0:$ Proportion of male and female smokers are same, $p̂_{Male-Smokers} = p̂_{Female-Smokers}$
  • Alternative hypothesis: $H_A:$ Proportion of male and female smokers are not same, $p̂_{Male-Smokers} \neq p̂_{Female-Smokers}$

Step 2: Decide the significance level¶

  • Selecting α = 0.05

Step 3: Identify the test statistic¶

  • Since we have to check if the proportion for two samples of Smokers $p̂_{Male-Smokers}$ and $p̂_{Female-Smokers}$ are significantly different and sample size is above 30, selecting z-test of proportion for two samples.
$$z = {\dfrac {(p̂_1-p̂_2)}{{\sqrt {p̂\left(1-p̂\right)}}{\sqrt{{\dfrac {1}{n_1}}+{\dfrac {1}{n_2}}}}}}$$

Step 4: Calculate p value¶

Step 4D - Is the distribution of bmi across women with no children, one child and two children, the same?¶

Step 1: State the null and alternative hypothesis:¶

  • Null hypothesis: $H_0:$ Distribution of BMI across women with no child, one child and two children are same, $\mu_{0-Child} = \mu_{1-Child} = \mu_{2-Children}$
  • Alternative hypothesis: $H_A:$ At least one $\mu$ is significantly different among $\mu$ of BMI distribution in women with no child, one child and two children.

Step 2: Decide the significance level¶

  • Selecting α = 0.05

Step 3: Identify the test statistic¶

  • Since we have to check if the distribution for more than two samples of BMI across women with $\mu_{0-Child}$, $\mu_{1-Child}$ and $\mu_{2-Children}$ are significantly different among each other, selecting analysis of variance (ANOVA), as it can determine whether the mean of one among three or more groups are different.
$$F-statistic = {\dfrac {\dfrac {SSB}{m-1}}{\dfrac {SSW}{m(n-1)}}}$$

Step 4: Calculate p value¶

# Calculate p-value
model = ols('BMI ~ Children', data = df_Child).fit() #'Values ~ Category'(m)
aov_table = sm.stats.anova_lm(model, typ=2)
print(aov_table) # (SSB=(SumSq/df))/(SSW=(SumSq/df)), F-Statistic, P-Value

                sum_sq     df         F    PR(>F)
Children     24.590123    2.0  0.334472  0.715858
Residual  20695.661583  563.0       NaN       NaN

Step 5: Decide to 'Reject' or 'Fail to reject' the null hypothesis¶

  • Statistical evidence, p-value is 0.715858 and > 0.05 so we 'Fail to reject the null hypothesis'.
  • Supporting $H_0:$ Distribution of BMI across no child, one child and two children are same, $\mu_{0-Child} = \mu_{1-Child} = \mu_{2-Children}$

Summary¶

Data provided insurance.csv had 1338 observation (rows) and 7 variables (columns). It did not have any missing values. It contained a duplicate value that was dropped before analysis.

Seven columns contained below attributes:

Age: A 'Uniform Distribution' of discrete variables from 18 to 64 years. The counts for age 18 and 19 years are more than double in comparison to rest of the age groups. Mean age is 39 years

Gender: A binary categorical variable had 49.5% females and 50.5% males. Proportion of males in southeast are 4% more relative to females in same region.

BMI: A 'Normally Distributed' continuous variable with median of 30.4 and mean of 30.66 that is very close to symmetric with a small positive skew of 0.28. It has few outliers on the right side of distribution that are beyond 1.5 times of IQR. There is no significant difference in BMI between males and females at a p-value of 0.089 that is greater than 0.05 α. It is also statistically evident that BMI of women with no child, one child or two children are same with a p-value of 0.7158 which is greater than the considered significance level of 0.05.

Children: A discrete variable with values ranging from 0 to 5 dependents. 42.9% of primary beneficiaries do not have children, 24.2% have one child, 18% have two children, 11.7% have three, 1.9% with four and 1.3% with 5 children.

Smoker: A binary categorical variable with 20.5% being smokers. Among the smokers’ proportion of male smokers are 6% higher than female smokers. It is statistically evident with a p-value of 0.0053 which is lower than 0.05 significance level, that proportion of male and female smokers are significantly different.

Region: A nominal categorical variable mentioning beneficiary's residential area in the US, northeast, southeast, southwest, northwest. Proportion of smokers in southeast are 5% more than average smokers of US. Proportion of primary beneficiaries with no or one child are 7% higher in Southeast relative to Northwest.

Charges: A continuous variable that shows individual medical costs billed by health insurance. Median of 9386 and mean of 13279 shows a huge right skew by 1.51, if considered as a whole. It also has some outliers on the right side beyond 1.5 times of IQR when the charges are considered as one data.

Pearson correlation heatmap showed a correlation of 0.3 and 0.2 for ‘Age’ and ‘BMI’ respectively with ‘Charges’. Further analysis revealed that charges vary based on 'Smoker', 'Non-Smoker', ‘BMI’ and ‘Age’. Charges for 'Smokers' are higher than 'Non-Smokers' and it increases further if they are above 30.4 'BMI'. Charges gradually increase based on ‘Age’ within these three categories.
